57#include <openssl/asn1.h>
58
59#include <openssl/err.h>
60#include <openssl/mem.h>
61
62
63void *ASN1_dup(i2d_of_void *i2d, d2i_of_void *d2i, void *x)
64 {
65 unsigned char *b,*p;
66 const unsigned char *p2;
67 int i;
68 char *ret;
69
70 if (x == NULL) return(NULL);
71
72 i=i2d(x,NULL);
73 b=OPENSSL_malloc(i+10);
74 if (b == NULL)
75 { OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(ASN1, ERR_R_MALLOC_FAILURE); return(NULL); }
76 p= b;
77 i=i2d(x,&p);
78 p2= b;
79 ret=d2i(NULL,&p2,i);
80 OPENSSL_free(b);
81 return(ret);
82 }
83
84/* ASN1_ITEM version of dup: this follows the model above except we don't need
85 * to allocate the buffer. At some point this could be rewritten to directly dup
86 * the underlying structure instead of doing and encode and decode. */
87void *ASN1_item_dup(const ASN1_ITEM *it, void *x)
88 {
89 unsigned char *b = NULL;
90 const unsigned char *p;
91 long i;
92 void *ret;
93
94 if (x == NULL) return(NULL);
95
96 i=ASN1_item_i2d(x,&b,it);
97 if (b == NULL)
98 { OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(ASN1, ERR_R_MALLOC_FAILURE); return(NULL); }
99 p= b;
100 ret=ASN1_item_d2i(NULL,&p,i, it);
101 OPENSSL_free(b);
102 return(ret);
103 }
